{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> νύξ</b>, νυκτός, ἡ, <br /> <b>night</b>: either generally, <b>mght-season</b> (opposed to day), or <b>a night,</b> ν. ἀμβροσίη [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 24.363; ν. ἄμβροτος 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.330 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; but ν. ὀλοή[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 19, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 16.567, compare below 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], III; νυκτός <b>by night,</b> as <i>adverb</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 13.278, etc.; οὔτε ν. οὔτ᾽ ἐξ ἡμέρας 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 780 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; νυκτὸς ἔτι <b>while it was</b> still <b>night,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.10; also τῆς νυκτός 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor 78.3, 148; ν. τῆσδε 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 21 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἄκρας ν. at dead of <b>night,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 285 (but ἄκρῃ νυκτί at \">Refs</a>]<b>night</b>-fall, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Aratus Epicus 775, ἀκρόθι νυκτός\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] on the verge of dawn, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 308) \">Refs</a>]; ἀωρὶ νυκτός, τῶν νυκτῶν, see at {ἀωρί}: in <i>plural</i>, τῶν νυκτῶν <b>at nights,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 668: rarely, νυκτί 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.12; ν. τῇδε 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 644 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; νύκτα <b>the night</b> long, νύκτα φυλάσσειν to watch <b>the night</b> through, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 10.312, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.466: _plural_, νύκτας ἰαύειν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.325, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.154, etc.; δύω νύκτας, τρεῖς ν., [prev. work] 388, 17.515 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: in <i>Attic dialect</i>, ὅλην τὴν ν. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pherecrates Comicus 177, 4th c.BC: Amphis Comicus 20.4; τὴν νύχθ᾽ ὅλην 4th c.BC: Eubulus Comicus 3; τὰς νύκτας 4th-3rd c.BC: Diphilus Comicus 32.14; ὅλας γε καὶ πάσας τὰς ν. 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Symposium” 4.54; νύκτας τε καὶ ἦμαρ 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.490; νύκτας τε καὶ ἡμέρας 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 151a; οὔτε νύκτ᾽ οὔθ᾽ ἡμέραν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 187; τὴν νύχθ᾽ ὅλην τήν θ᾽ ἡμέραν 4th c.BC: Eubulus Comicus 53.1 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; νύκτα ἡμέραν ποιούμενος ἀπόστειλον (κατάπεμψον), i. e. without delay, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PCair.Zen.” 314.7, “PSI” 5.514.3 (both 3rd c.BC) \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; μέσαι νύκτες <b>midnight,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica 52, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 621b; περὶ μ. νύκτας 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 7.8.12; ἐν μέσῳ νυκτῶν [prev. author] “Cyr.” 5.3.52; πρωΐτερον μέσων νυκτῶν 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 8.101; ἔξω μέσων ν. 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 54.26. \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> frequently with Preps., ἀνὰ νύκτα by <b>night,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.80 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἀνὰ πᾶσαν ν. all <b>night</b> through, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 1.32.4; διὰ νύκτα 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 19.66, etc. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; εἰς νύκτα, εἰς τὴν ν., towards <b>night,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Cynegeticus” 11.4, “HG” 4.6.7 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἐν νυττί (νυκτί), opposed to πεδ᾽ ἀμέραν, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Leg.Gort.” 2.14, “SIG” 527.40 (Dreros, 3rd c.BC) \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; κατὰ νύκτα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Fragmenta” 561 (Lyric poetry) \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὑπὸ νύκτα to wards <b>nightfall,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 4.67, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Agesilaus” 2.19 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; μετὰ νύκτας by <b>night,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 6.6 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; μεθ᾽ ἡμέραν καὶ διὰ νυκτός all through <b>the night,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Critias” 117e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἐκ νυκτός after <b>nightfall,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 1.4.2, LXX.Isa.26.9, etc.; ἐκ πολλῆς ἔτι νυκτός 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis 6.67; ἐκ νυκτῶν 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 460, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 287, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Rhesus” 13, 17 (both _anapaest meter_); ἐκ νυκτὸς εἰς νύκτα 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Axiochus” 368b \">LXX+6th c.BC+</a>]; πόρρω τῶν νυκτῶν far into <b>the night,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Smp.” 217d, “Prt.” 310c \">Refs</a>]; ἐπὶ νυκτί by <b>night,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 8.529; ἐφ᾽ ἡμέρῃ αἱ δ᾽ ἐπὶ νυκτί 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 102; ἐν νυκτί 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 653, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Symposium” 1.9, etc.; ὀψίᾳ ἐν ν. 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “I.” 4(3).36; ἐν ν. τῇ νῦν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 16; νύκτεσσιν ἔν θ᾽ ἁμέραις 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.130. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> in <i>plural</i>, <b>watches</b> of the night, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 256 \">Refs</a>]; three such, παροίχωκεν δὲ πλέων νὺξ τῶν δύο μοιράων, τριτάτη δ᾽ ἔτι μοῖρα λέλειπται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 10.252 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τρίχα νυκτὸς ἔην, for τρίτον μέρος τῆς νυκτὸς ἦν, it was the third watch, i. e. next before morning, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 12.312. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <i>metaphorically</i> of darkness, νυκτὶ καλύψαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.23, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 20.351, etc. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <i>metaphorically</i> of death, ἀμφὶ δὲ ὄσσε κελαινὴ ν. ἐκάλυψε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.310, +others; ν. Ἅιδης τε 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 660. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> in Comparisons, of anything dark and direful, νυκτὶ ἐοικώς like <b>night,</b> of Apollo in his wrath, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.47, compare 12.463, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.606 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τάδε νυκτὶ ἐΐσκει what is here he like ns <b>to night,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 20.362 \">Refs</a>]; ὀλεθρία ν., of a great calamity, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1684 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> Νύξ as <i>proper name</i>, <b>the goddess of Night,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.259, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 17, “Th.” 123, 211; N. ὀλοή [prev. work] 224. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> <b>the night-</b> or <b>evening-quarter of heaven, the West,</b> πρὸς νυκτός [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 275. (Cf. Latin \">Refs</a>]<b>nox,</b> Lithuanian <i>naktis,</i> Gothic <i>nahts,</i> etc.)","strongNumber":"G3571","accentedUnicode":"νύξ","shortDef":"night, evening","mediumDef":"night, evening <br /><b>night,</b> <ref='Mat.2.14; 28:13'>Mt. 2:14; 28:13</ref>; <ref='Jhn.3.2'>Jn. 3:2</ref>; <i>metaphorically</i> spiritual <b>night,</b> moral <b>darkness,</b> <ref='Rom.13.12'>Rom. 13:12;</ref> <ref='1Th.5.5'>1Thess. 5:5</ref>","stepGloss":"night","stepTransliteration":"nux","count":65,"_es_Definition":"noche","_zh_tw_Definition":"夜晚","_zh_Definition":"夜晚","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"đêm","_zh_tw_Gloss":"夜","_es_Gloss":"noche","_zh_Gloss":"夜"}]}